introduction: 1 A split-plot latin square (3 randomizations) study with 6 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2001-2005 at Dixon Spring Agricultural Research Center, IL investigating the effects of tillage and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Olson et al., 2010).

results_short: They found cover crops did not affect maize or soybean yields.

introduction: 1 A split-plot latin square (3 randomizations) study with 6 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2001-2005 at Dixon Spring Agricultural Research Center, IL investigating the effects of tillage and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Olson et al., 2010).
Trt_id1description: no winter cover crop, moldboard plow applied preceeding cash crop
Trt_id2description: maize: cereal rye / soybean: hairy vetch, moldboard plow preceeded cash crop planting
results_short: They found cover crops did not alter soil organic carbon levels in no-tillage, moldboard plow, and chisel plow systems compared to the same tillage system without cover crop.
Reviewers_results_long: For each tillage treatment with cover crops, there was no observable net increase in soil carbon sequestration when compared with the soil organic carbon levels for each tillage treatment without cover crops in 2000.
methods: 1 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), hairy vetch, cereal rye.  1 Plots were 20.25 sq m.

introduction: 2 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2006-2011 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cover crops species in a maize/soybean system (Kaspar et al., 2012).
Trt_id2description: oat cover crop, yields of soybean
results_short: They found no impact of rye cover crops on maize and soybean yields, but oat cover crops reduced yields four out of six years.
Reviewers_results_long: The effect of cover crops on maize and soybean yields was dependent on the cover crop. Rye cover crops had no effect on soybean or maize yields from 2005 to 2010 compared to winter fallow. Oat cover crops, alternatively, reduced maize and soybean yields from 2005 to 2008 compared to winter fallow. Cash crop yields were unaffected by oat cover crops in 2009 and 2010.
methods: 2 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 2.5 x 10^6 seeds/ha, oat @ 3.7 x 10^6 seeds/ha. 2 Cover crops were no-till drilled between September-October and between August-September. 2 Plots were 930.25 sq m.
citation: 2 Kaspar, T.C., Jaynes, D.B., Parkin, T.B., Moorman, T.B. & Singer, J.W. (2012). Effectiveness of oat and rye cover crops in reducing nitrate losses in drainage water. Agricultural Water Management, 110: 25-33. DOI: 10.1016/j.agwat.2012.03.010

introduction: 3 A randomized complete block design study with 3 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2012-2015 in Lexington, IL investigating the effects of cover crops species + management in a maize system (Grebliunas et al., 2016).
Trt_id2description: winter rye cover crop, corn crop
results_short: They found similar amounts of water extractable organic carbon following three winters of cover crops (winter rye, cereal rye, and tillage radish) compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "Within three years of cover crop implementation, cereal rye, and tillage radish residues have not increased the water extractable organic content in soils relative to the other treatments. The lack of difference may be attributed to the relatively short time period that cover crops were planted within this site."

introduction: 4 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 2 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2011-2013 in Cerro Gordo, IL, Malta, IL, Pana, IL investigating the effects of field area and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Welch et al., 2016).
Trt_id2description: forage radish for winter cover crop
results_short: They found no impact of winter cover crops on the amount of ammonium in soil compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "There was no effect of field area or cover crop treatments on available nitrogen (ammonium & nitrate)."
methods: 4 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), forage radish @ 12.3 kg/ha, forage radish + buckwheat @ 12.3 and 67.2 kg/ha, forage radish + hairy vetch + cereal rye @ 12.3, 16.8, and 56 kg/ha. 4Cover crops were broadcasted. 4 Plots were 36 sq m.

introduction: 4 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 2 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2011-2013 in Cerro Gordo, IL, Malta, IL, Pana, IL investigating the effects of field area and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Welch et al., 2016).
Trt_id2description: forage radish for winter cover crop
results_short: They found a marginally significant (p = 0.621) reduction in plant available phosphorous with a cover crop mixture of forage radish, hairy vetch, and cereal rye.
Reviewers_results_long: Forage radish and forage radish mixed with buckwheat as cover crops had no effect on plant available phosphorous compared to winter fallow. The only cover crop treatment to reduce plant available phosphorous levels was the three way mixture of forage radish, hairy vetch, and cereal rye.
methods: 4 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), forage radish @ 12.3 kg/ha, forage radish + buckwheat @ 12.3 and 67.2 kg/ha, forage radish + hairy vetch + cereal rye @ 12.3, 16.8, and 56 kg/ha. 4Cover crops were broadcasted. 4 Plots were 36 sq m.
citation: 4 Welch, R.Y., Behnke, G.D., Davis, A.S., Masiunas, J. & Villamil, M.B. (2016). Using cover crops in headlands of organic grain farms: Effects on soil properties, weeds and crop yields. Agriculture, Ecosystems and Environment, 216: 322-332. DOI: 10.1016/j.agee.2015.10.014

results_short: They found a marginally significant (p = 0.621) reduction in plant available phosphorous with a cover crop mixture of forage radish, hairy vetch, and cereal rye.

introduction: 4 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 2 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2011-2013 in Cerro Gordo, IL, Malta, IL, Pana, IL investigating the effects of field area and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Welch et al., 2016).
Trt_id2description: forage radish for winter cover crop
results_short: They found increased penetration resistance with a cover crop mixture of forage radish, hairy vetch, and rye in one area (non-headlands) compared to winter fallow. Penetration resistance was unaffected by all other cover crop treatments.
Reviewers_results_long: "Cover crop treatment of forage radish, hairy vetch, cereal rye seemed to increase the penetration resistance slightly within the non-headlands areas in comparison with the other treatments likely related to the cover crops still growing and extracting water from the profile at the time of measurement."
methods: 4 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), forage radish @ 12.3 kg/ha, forage radish + buckwheat @ 12.3 and 67.2 kg/ha, forage radish + hairy vetch + cereal rye @ 12.3, 16.8, and 56 kg/ha. 4Cover crops were broadcasted. 4 Plots were 36 sq m.

introduction: 4 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 2 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2011-2013 in Cerro Gordo, IL, Malta, IL, Pana, IL investigating the effects of field area and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Welch et al., 2016).
Trt_id2description: forage radish/hairy vetch/cereal rye mix for winter cover crop
results_short: They found reductions in weed biomass when forage radish, hairy vetch, and cereal rye were planted as a mixture compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Weed biomass was reduced when forage radish was grown alone or grown with buckwheat compared to winter fallow, but this reduction was not statistically significant. When forage radish, hairy vetch, and cereal rye were mixed weed biomass decreased by more than two-thirds compared to winter fallow.
methods: 4 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), forage radish @ 12.3 kg/ha, forage radish + buckwheat @ 12.3 and 67.2 kg/ha, forage radish + hairy vetch + cereal rye @ 12.3, 16.8, and 56 kg/ha. 4Cover crops were broadcasted. 4 Plots were 36 sq m.

introduction: 5 A split-split-plot randomized experimental design study with 4 replications was conducted at 13 sites from 2013-2014 and 2014-2015 in AR, IN, IL, MO, OH, TN investigating the effects of cover crops, crop herbicide resistance, and herbicides in a soybean system (Loux et al., 2017).
Response_var: control of common waterhemp (21 days post planting)
Trt_id1description: no cover crop, no herbicide treatments
Trt_id2description: "other" cover crop (spring oat, Italian ryegrass, forage radish), no herbicide treatments
results_short: They found increased control of waterhemp with cereal rye cover crops compared to winter fallow. The 'other' cover crops studied did not affect the control of waterhemp.
Reviewers_results_long: Cereal rye consistently improved the percent control of waterhemp in this study 21 days after planting  and after the harvest of cash crops compared to winter fallow and the 'other' cover crops studied. There was no benefit in control of waterhemp with the inclusion of the 'other' cover crops examined in this study.
methods: 5 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 67-134 kg/ha, "other" - spring oat, Italian ryegrass, forage radish @ 67-101, 22, and 6.7-11 kg/ha. 5 Cover crops were no-till drilled in the fall. 5 Plots were an undescribed size.
citation: 5 Loux, M.M., Dobbels, A.F., Bradley, K.W., Johnson, W.G., Young, B.G., Spaunhorst, D.J., Norsworthy, J.K., Palhano, M. & Steckel, L.E. (2017). Influence of cover crops on management of Amaranthus Species in glyphosate- and glufosinate-resistant soybean. Weed Technology, 31: 487-495. DOI: 10.1017/wet.2017.30

results_short: They found increased control of Palmer amaranth with cereal rye cover crops compared to winter fallow. The 'other' cover crops studied increased control of Palmer amaranth early in the growing season, but by the autumn there was Palmer amaranth was not effectively controlled compared to winter fallow.

introduction: 6 A split-split-plot randomized experimental design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1989-1991 in Columbia, MO investigating the effects of cover crops, cover crop termination, and herbicides in a maize system (Johnson et al., 1993).
Trt_id1description: soybean stubble (no cover crop), tillage to kill weeds
Trt_id2description: hairy vetch cover crop, tillage to terminate cover crop
results_short: They found cocklebur was poorly controlled with either winter rye or hairy vetch with tillage, but was effectively controlled with either cover crop in a mowed system.
Reviewers_results_long: When tillage was used to terminate cover crops in the spring, control of cocklebur was reduced with hairy vetch compared to winter rye and winter fallow. However,  when  cover crops were terminated with mowing, both hairy vetch and winter rye increased control over cocklebur compared to winter fallow.
methods: 6 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 157 kg/ha, hairy vetch @ 22 kg/ha. 6 Cover crops were hand seeded in September. 6 Plots were 9 sq m.
citation: 6 Johnson, G.A., Defelice, M.S. & Helsel, Z.R. (1993). Cover crop management and weed control in Corn (Zea mays). Weed Technology, 7(2): 425-430. DOI: www.jstor.org/stable/3987624

introduction: 7 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2005-2007 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cover crops + manure in a maize system (Jarecki et al., 2009).
Trt_id1description: no winter cover crop, no manure
results_short: They found nitrous oxide emisisons were unaffected by cover crop mixtures of winter rye and oat both while the cover crops were growing and over the entire year.
Reviewers_results_long: "The presence of a cover crop did not significantly effect total nitous oxide emissions in the treatments receiving 202 kg manure N/ha. While there was a trend of lower mean nitrous oxide emission in the cover crop no manure treatment as compared to the no cover crop no manure treatment, this difference was not significant."
methods: 7 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye + oat @ 70/30 mix. 7Cover crops were broadcasted. 7 Plots were 14.44 sq m.
citation: 7 Jarecki, M.K., Parkin, T.B., Chan, A.S.L., Kaspar, T.C., Moorman, T.B., Singer, J.W., Kerr, B.J., Hatfield, J.L. & Jones, R. (2009). Response_var: density of Lamim spp. (Henbit and purple deadnettle) after 5 years
results_short: They found generally no difference in the density of henbit and purple deadnettle in the cover crop treatments (Italian ryegrass and winter wheat) compared to the untreated controls.
Reviewers_results_long: The density of winter annual weeds, Lamim spp. (Henbit and purple deadnettle), was generally unaffected winter wheat and Italian ryegrass cover crops in both the spring and autumn in 2006 and 2007 at two locations. The only exceptions being in 2007 at the Vincennes, IN location, both winter wheat and Italian ryegrass had increased densities of Lamium spp. compared to the nontreated check.
methods: 8 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), Italian ryegrass @ 34 kg/ha, winter wheat @ 67 kg/ha. 8Cover crops were broadcasted and no-till drilled. 8 Plots were 82.81 sq m.

introduction: 8 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 6 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2006-2008 in West Lafayette, IN, Vincennes, IN investigating the effects of crop rotation and weed management in a maize/soybean system (Mock et al., 2012).
Response_var: total density of winter weeds after 5 years
results_short: They found after 5 years of the cover crop treatments (Italian ryegrass and winter wheat) winter annual weed densities were generally similar to the untreated controls.
Reviewers_results_long:
"Cover crops were generally similar to the nontreated check. One exception was total winter annual weeds where the Italian ryegrass cover crop had higher weed density than did the wheat cover crop or the nontreated check. The high level of winter mortality of Italian ryegrass at this site may have inhibited the ability of this cover crop to suppress weed growth. In addition, the soil disturbance from the drill may have promoted additional weed density, resulting in higher weed density than the nontreated check had.
over a fairly wide range of temperatures, but the rate of SCN
growth and development is strongly temperature dependent.
The rate of SCN egg development increases linearly with
temperature between 15 and 30 C but ceases all together at
temperatures below 10 C (Alston and Schmitt 1988).
Previous studies have shown that henbit and purple deadnettle
can support SCN reproduction at levels comparable to SCNsusceptible
soybean in the greenhouse (Creech et al. 2007a;
Venkatesh et al. 2000). In the field, however, soil temperatures
are not optimal for SCN development at the time that
winter annual weeds are actively growing. Soil temperature
data collected in these plots over the course of the study
suggest that the period of overlap between high SCN activity
and winter annual weed growth is likely limited to a few weeks
in early autumn and late spring (data not shown).
Although the ability of SCN to reproduce on henbit and
purple deadnettle under field conditions in Indiana, Illinois,
and Ohio has also been confirmed (Creech et al. 2005,
2007b), the results of this 5-yr study suggest that SCN
reproduction on winter annual weeds appears to contribute
little, if any, to the overall SCN population levels in the field.
Nelson et al. (2006) reported an inconsistent response of SCN
to winter annual weed management in Missouri where the few
treatment differences that were observed in a single year were
not significant in another year.
Crop Yield. Soybean yield varied SCN hatching, root penetration, and development occur over a fairly wide range of temperatures, but the rate of SCN growth and development is strongly temperature dependent. The rate of SCN egg development increases linearly with temperature between 15 and 30 C but ceases all together at temperatures below 10 C (Alston and Schmitt 1988). Previous studies have shown that henbit and purple deadnettle can support SCN reproduction at levels comparable to SCN susceptible soybean in the greenhouse (Creech et al. 2007a; Venkatesh et al. 2000). In the field, however, soil temperatures are not optimal for SCN development at the time that winter annual weeds are actively growing. Soil temperature data collected in these plots over the course of the study suggest that the period of overlap between high SCN activity and winter annual weed growth is likely limited to a few weeks in early autumn and late spring (data not shown). introduction: 9 A strip-block randomized complete block design study with 4 or 3 replications was conducted at 3 sites from 1987-1988 and 1987-1989 in Custar, OH, South Charleston, OH, Ripley, OH investigating the effects of cover crops/planting date in a soybean system (Hammond, 1991).

introduction: 10 A randomized complete block design study with 5 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1990-1996 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cover crops in a soybean system (Johnson et al., 1998).
Response_var: maize grain yield after soybean overseeded with cc (years 5 & 6)
results_short: They found no impact of oat cover crops on maize yields compared to winter fallow, but rye and oat/rye mixtures reduced maize yields.
Reviewers_results_long: "The rye and oat-rye mixture treatments significantly reduced corn yield compared with the control and oat plots in both of the years that data are available. Apparently, the rye and oat-rye cover crops stressed the corn plants during early vegetative growth. The oat cover crop plants are winter-killed in Iowa, so there is no direct resource competition with the corn in the spring."
methods: 10 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), oat @ 3,800,000 seeds/ha, cereal rye @ 3,800,000 seeds/ha, cereal rye + oat @ 3,800,000 seeds/ha. 10Cover crops were overseeded into soybean. 10 Plots were 14.44 sq m.
citation: 10 Johnson, T.J., Kaspar, T.C., Kohler, K.A., Corak, S.J., & Logsdon, S.D. (1998). Oat and rye overseeded into soybean as fall cover crops in the upper Midwest. Journal of Soil and Water Conservation, 53(3): 276-279. DOI: 1abc

introduction: 10 A randomized complete block design study with 5 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1990-1996 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cover crops in a soybean system (Johnson et al., 1998).
results_short: They found rye, oat, and rye/oat mixtures of cover crops did not affect soybean yields compared to no winter cover crops.
Reviewers_results_long: "The soybean yield averages for 1994 through 1996 were numerically lower, but not statistically different from the control."
methods: 10 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), oat @ 3,800,000 seeds/ha, cereal rye @ 3,800,000 seeds/ha, cereal rye + oat @ 3,800,000 seeds/ha. 10Cover crops were overseeded into soybean. 10 Plots were 14.44 sq m.

introduction: 11 A strip-block split-plot randomized complete block design study with 3 or 4 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 1994-1995 and 1995-1996 in Ithaca, NE investigating the effects of cover crops and irrigation in a soybean system (Williams et al., 2000).
results_short: They found barley, rye, triticale, and wheat cover crops reduced soybean grain yield in 1995.
Reviewers_results_long: In rainfed systems, soybean yields were higher with winter fallow compared to  all the cover crops in the first year of the study. In the second year, soybean yields improved with cover crops such that they were similar to winter fallow with wheat resulting in higher yields. Among the cover crops, wheat consistently resulted in the highest grain yields.
methods: 11 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: wheat cv. Arapho @ 78.4 kg/ha, winter triticale cv. Newcastle @ 78.4 kg/ha, barley cv. Perkins @ 78.4 kg/ha, cereal rye cv. VNS @ 78.4 kg/ha, hairy vetch @ 35.8 kg/ha, winter fallow (control), barley @ 78.4 kg/ha, cereal rye @ 78.4 kg/ha, triticale @ 156.4 kg/ha, wheat @ 78.4 kg/ha. 11Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 11 Plots were 21.16 sq m.
citation: 11 Williams, M.M. II, Mortensen, D.A., & Doran, J.W. (2000). No-tillage soybean performance in cover crops for weed management in western Corn Belt. Journal of Soil and Water Conservation, 55(1): 79-84. DOI: 2abc

introduction: 13 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 5 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1994-1997 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cover crops and wheel traffic in a maize/soybean system (Kaspar et al., 2001).
results_short: They found no differences in soil bulk density among oat, rye, and winter fallow from 1996 to 1998.
Reviewers_results_long: Over the course of this three year study, oat and rye cover crops had no effect on soil bulk density compared to the control (winter fallow).
methods: 13 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), oat cv. Ogle @ 380 kg/ha, cereal rye @ 380 kg/ha. 13Cover crops were drop seeded (interseeded into soybean). 13 Plots were 14.5161 sq m.
citation: 13 Kaspar, T.C., Radke, J.K, & Laflen, J.M. (2001). Small grain cover crops and wheel traffic effects on infiltration, runoff, and erosion. Journal of Soil and Water Conservation, 56(2): 160-164. DOI: 4abc

introduction: 13 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 5 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1994-1997 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cover crops and wheel traffic in a maize/soybean system (Kaspar et al., 2001).
results_short: They found rates of water infiltration improved with rye cover crop in only one year compared to winter fallow. Oat cover crops did not alter water infiltration rates compared to winter fallow or rye cover crops.
Reviewers_results_long: "In 1998, the rye cover crop incrased the infiltration rate by 16% and reduced runoff by 10% compared with the control. The infiltration rate of the oat cover crop treatment, although not significantly different, was intermediate to that of the control and rye treatment."

results_short: They found cover crops inconsistently affected interrill errosion rates.
Reviewers_results_long: Reductions in interrill erosion rates were observed with rye cover crops two of the three years compared to winter fallow. Oat cover crops reduced interrill erosion as well in one year, but had similar interrill erosion rates as winter fallow in the other two years of the study.

introduction: 13 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 5 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1994-1997 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cover crops and wheel traffic in a maize/soybean system (Kaspar et al., 2001).
results_short: They found rye cover crops increased soil volumetric water content in one out of three years of the study, while oat had no affect compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Rye cover crops improved the mean volumetric water content by the third year of this study compared to winter fallow and oat cover crops. For the first two years of the study, there were no differences in mean soil volumetric water content among rye, oat and winter fallow.

introduction: 14 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1998-2001 in Lamberton, MN investigating the effects of cropping system and drainage tiles in a maize/soybean system (Strock et al., 2004).
Response_var: concentration of total NO3-N in ground water under maize
results_short: They found rye cover crop either reduced or had no affect on the total nitrate concentrations in the ground water compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "Averaged across three years, the cropping system with rye cover crop reduced sub-surface drainage discharge by 11% and nitrate loss in subsurface drainage discharge by 13% compared with the cropping system with no cover crop in this study."
methods: 14 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 180 kg/ha. 14 Cover crops were no-till drilled between September-October. 14 Plots were 187.69 sq m.
citation: 14 Strock, J.S., Porter, P.M., & Russelle, M.P. (2004). Cover cropping to reduce nitrate loss through subsurface drainage in the Northern U.S. Corn Belt. Journal of Environmental Quality, 33(3): 1010-116. DOI: 5abc

introduction: 14 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1998-2001 in Lamberton, MN investigating the effects of cropping system and drainage tiles in a maize/soybean system (Strock et al., 2004).
results_short: They found rye cover crops had relatively little affect on soil nitrate levels compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: While soil nitrate levels varied with crop year and sampling event (preceeding the planting and following harvest of maize or soybean) rye cover crops reduced nitrate levels in only one sampling event (preceeding soybean in first year of the study) over the course of three years.
methods: 14 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 180 kg/ha. 14 Cover crops were no-till drilled between September-October. 14 Plots were 187.69 sq m.
citation: 14 Strock, J.S., Porter, P.M., & Russelle, M.P. (2004). Cover cropping to reduce nitrate loss through subsurface drainage in the Northern U.S. Corn Belt. Journal of Environmental Quality, 33(3): 1010-116. DOI: 5abc

introduction: 14 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1998-2001 in Lamberton, MN investigating the effects of cropping system and drainage tiles in a maize/soybean system (Strock et al., 2004).
results_short: They found rye cover crops did not affect maize or soybean yields compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Maize and soybean yields were unaffected by winter cover crops compared to winter fallow.
methods: 14 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 180 kg/ha. 14 Cover crops were no-till drilled between September-October. 14 Plots were 187.69 sq m.

introduction: 14 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1998-2001 in Lamberton, MN investigating the effects of cropping system and drainage tiles in a maize/soybean system (Strock et al., 2004).
Response_var: total NO3-N lost from soil under maize
results_short: They found rye cover crop either reduced or had no affect on the total nitrate losses per hectare compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Rye cover crops had relatively little effect on the amount of total nitrate lost from soybean and maize systems during this three year study. Reductions in total nitrate were observed in the first year in maize and in the second year in soybean (p = 0.1).
methods: 14 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 180 kg/ha. 14 Cover crops were no-till drilled between September-October. 14 Plots were 187.69 sq m.
citation: 14 Strock, J.S., Porter, P.M., & Russelle, M.P. (2004). Cover cropping to reduce nitrate loss through subsurface drainage in the Northern U.S. Corn Belt. Journal of Environmental Quality, 33(3): 1010-116. DOI: 5abc

introduction: 15 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2005-2007 in Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cropping system + fertilizer in a soybean/maize system (Cambardella et al., 2010).
Response_var: total (NO3+NH4)-N from soil profile (0-120 cm) in crop interrow
Trt_id1description: no winter cover crop, no liquid swine manure
Trt_id2description: rye/oat winter cover crop, no liquid manure
results_short: They found rye/oat cover crops decreased the amount of total nitrogen available in soils.
Reviewers_results_long: Total soil nitrate (nitrate + ammonium) in the 0-120 cm depth decreased in both the row and interrow positions when rye/oat cover crops were grown compared to winter fallow.
methods: 15 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Maton + oat cv. Jerry @ 26,000,000 and 1,100,000 seeds/ha, winter fallow (control). 15 Cover crops were drop seeded between August-September. 15 Plots were 14.44 sq m.
citation: 15 Cambardella, C.A., Moorman, T.B., & Singer, J.W. (2010). Soil nitrogen response to coupling cover crops with manure injection. Nutrient Cycling in Agroecosystems, 87: 383-393. DOI: 10.1007/s10705-010-9345-9

introduction: 16 A completely randomized design study with 6 to 8 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2007-2009 in Brookings, SD investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Lundgren & Fergen, 2010).
Response_var: diversity of predators in soil column (Evenness J)
results_short: They found slender wheatgrass had no affect on the diversity of invertebrate predators.

introduction: 17 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2006-2009 in Pocahontas County, IA investigating the effects of cropping system in a maize/soybean system (Qi et al., 2010).
results_short: They found average annual soil water storage was relatively unaffected by rye cover crops.
Reviewers_results_long: Rye cover crops had little effect on the average annual soil water storage compared to winter fallow except for in the first year of the study in maize where annual soil water storage increased with rye cover crop.
methods: 17 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 100 kg/ha. 17 Cover crops were no-till drilled in October. 17 Plots were 231.04 sq m.
citation: 17 Qi, Z., Helmers, M.J., Kaleita, A.L. (2010). Soil water dynamics under various agricultural land covers on a subsurface drained field in north-central Iowa, USA. Agricultural Water Management, 98: 665-674. DOI: 10.1016/j.agwat.2010.11.004

introduction: 19 A paired tests survey study with 22 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2005-2006 in statewide, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a variable system (Koch et al., 2012).
Response_var: infestation rating of soybean fields with Aphis glycines (0 = 0 aphids/plant; 1 = 1-10 /plant; 2 = 11-100/plant; 3 = 101-1,000/plant; 4 = >1,000/plant)
results_short: They found rye cover crops significantly reduced the number of aphids (Aphis glycines) colonizing each infested plant compared with winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Over the course of a single field season, the infestation of Aphis glycine rating was lower in soybean fields with rye than without.
methods: 19 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. variable, winter fallow (control).  19 Plots were an undescribed size.
citation: 19 Koch, R.L., Porter, P.M., Harbur, M.M., Abrahamson, M.D., Wyckhuys, K.A.G., Ragsdale, D.W., Buchman, K., Sexen, Z., & Heimpel, G.E. (2012). Response of soybean insects to an autumn-seeded rye cover crop. Environmental Entomology, 41(4): 750-760. DOI: 10.1603/EN11168

introduction: 19 A paired tests survey study with 22 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2005-2006 in statewide, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a variable system (Koch et al., 2012).
Response_var: proportion of soybean plants infested with Aphis glycines per field (30 plants assessed / field)
results_short: They found rye cover crops significantly reduced the proportion of plants infested by Aphis glycines compared with winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Over the course of a single field season, the proportion of soybean plants infested with Aphis glycine was lower in soybean fields with rye than without.
methods: 19 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. variable, winter fallow (control).  19 Plots were an undescribed size.

introduction: 20 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2009-2012 in Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cover crops and fertilization rate in a maize/soybean system (Mitchell et al., 2013).
Trt_id1description: no winter cover crop, 0 kg fertilizer N / ha
Trt_id2description: rye winter cover crop, 0 kg fertilizer N / ha
results_short: They found rye cover crop had no affect on cumulative nitrous oxide emissions compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: The effect cover crops have on the cumulative nitros oxide emissions were inconsistent across fertilizer treatments. Generally, when no fertilizer is added the addition of rye cover crops reduced the cumulative nitrous oxide emissions. However, at medium fertilization rates (135 kg N / ha) cover crops increased emissions. There were no differences in emissions at high levels of fertilization (225 kg N / ha).
methods: 20 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 70 kg/ha. 20 Cover crops were drilled in October. 20 Plots were 37.21 sq m.
citation: 20 Mitchell, D.C., Castellano, M.J., Sawyer, J.E, & Pantoja, J. (2013). Cover crop effects on nitrous oxide emission: Role of mineralizable carbon. Soil Science Society of America Journal, 77: 1765-1773. DOI: 10.2136/sssaj2013.02.0074

introduction: 21 A grided sampling of 56 acre fields study with 1 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2008-2009 in west central, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Krueger et al., 2013).
results_short: They found winter rye cover crop reduced maize nitrogen uptake compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: The addition of a winter rye cover crop reduced maize yields and nitrogen uptake.
methods: 21 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 126 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 21 Cover crops were broadcasted in September. 21 Plots were an undescribed size.

introduction: 21 A grided sampling of 56 acre fields study with 1 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2008-2009 in west central, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Krueger et al., 2013).
Response_var: soil nitrate nitrogen (NO3-N) concentration in Spring, 0-60 cm
results_short: They found soil nitrate levels in the top 60 cm of soil were unaffected by rye cover crops in the fall, but between 60-90 cm nitrate levels were reduced with winter rye. Soil nitrate in the spring (0-60 cm depth) were also reduced with winter rye cover crops.
Reviewers_results_long: Winter rye cover crops reduced soil nitrate levels in the fall between 60-90 cm in depth and in the spring between 0-60 cm depth. In the fall, the top 60 cm of soil had similar soil nitrate levels with winter rye compared to winter fallow.
methods: 21 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 126 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 21 Cover crops were broadcasted in September. 21 Plots were an undescribed size.
citation: 21 Krueger, E.S., Baker, J.M., Ochsner, T.E., Wente, C.D., Feyereisen, G.W. & Reicosky, D.C. (2013). On-farm environmental assessment of corn silage production systems receiving liquid dairy manure. Journal of Soil and Water Conservation, 68(6): 438-449. DOI: 10.2489/jswc.68.6.438

introduction: 21 A grided sampling of 56 acre fields study with 1 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2008-2009 in west central, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Krueger et al., 2013).
Response_var: soil organic carbon (SOC) in fall following cover crop, 0-15cm
results_short: They found soil organic carbon levels descreased with winter rye cover crop compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: While the rye cover crop may have contributed to increased soil organic carbon concentration, the soil organic carbon in the fall of 2008 after rye was similar to previous years. This result, along with relatively high manure carbon additions (12 MG /ha) compared with rye aboveground biomass (0.9 MG / ha), suggests that one year of rye cover crop tilled into the soil was not likely the primary contributor to the observed increase in soil organic carbon concentration.
methods: 21 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 126 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 21 Cover crops were broadcasted in September. 21 Plots were an undescribed size.
citation: 21 Krueger, E.S., Baker, J.M., Ochsner, T.E., Wente, C.D., Feyereisen, G.W. & Reicosky, D.C. (2013). On-farm environmental assessment of corn silage production systems receiving liquid dairy manure. Journal of Soil and Water Conservation, 68(6): 438-449. DOI: 10.2489/jswc.68.6.438

introduction: 22 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2010-2012 in Arlington, WI investigating the effects of cover crop termination and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Silva, 2014).
Response_var: weed biomass after termination of cover crops
results_short: They found all of the cover crops (Austrian winter pea, hairy vetch, rye, winter barley, winter triticale) tested reduced weed biomass compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: In this two year study, each cover crop tested significantly reduced weed biomass compared to winter fallow  control. The cover crops that performed the best were winter rye (2010 & 2011), Austrian winter pea (2010, poor germination in 2011 led to no analysis of these plots), and Winter barley (2011 only).
methods: 22 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter triticale cv. Fridge @ 269 kg/ha, winter barley cv. McGregor @ 269 kg/ha, winter fallow (control), hairy vetch @ 33.6 kg/ha, cereal rye @ 269 kg/ha, Austrian winter peas @ 44.6 kg/ha. 22 Cover crops were no-till drilled in September. 22 Plots were 83.5396 sq m.
citation: 22 Silva, E.M. (2014). Screening five fall-sown cover crops for use in organic no-till crop production in the upper Midwest. Agroecology and Sustainable Food Systems, 38: 748-763. DOI: 10.1080/21683565.2014.901275

introduction: 22 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2010-2012 in Arlington, WI investigating the effects of cover crop termination and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Silva, 2014).
Response_var: weed density after termination of cover crops
results_short: They found in the first year of the study only Austrian winter pea reduced weed densities after the termination of cover crops, but in the second year all cover crop species except winter triticale significantly reduced weed density compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: In 2010, Austrian winter peas was the only cover crop species tested that reduced weed density more than winter fallow. In 2011, all cover crop species except winter triticale significantly reduced weed density compared to winter fallow. Austrian winter peas did not germinate well in the field.

introduction: 23 A randomized complete block design study with 2 replications was conducted at 3 sites from 2012-2013 at Agricultural Drainage Water Research Site, IA, Iowa State University Agronomy and Agricultural Engineering Research Farm, IA, Southeast Purdue Agricultural Center, IN investigating the effects of cash crop and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Daigh et al., 2014).
Response_var: soil water content at cash crop emergence, 10 cm depth
results_short: They found rye cover crops increased soil water content early in the growoing season at two of the three sites studies.
Reviewers_results_long: Generally, rye cover crops increased soil water content at two sites included in this study. Where in the soil profile (0-20 cm) and when these increases occurred (relative to planting the cash crop) varied between sites. The greatest increases were observed at the site with the largest amount of rye biomass incorporated into the soil.
methods: 23 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 100, 63, and 78 kg/ha dependent on site. 23 Cover crops were drilled in September. 23 Plots were 225 sq m or 324 sq m.
citation: 23 Daigh, E.L., Helmers, M.J., Kladivko, E., Zhou, X., Goeken, R., Cavdini, J., Barker, D., & Sawyer, J. (2014). Soil water during the drought of 2012 as affected by rye cover crops in fields in Iowa and Indiana. Journal of Soil and Water Conservation, 69(6): 564-573. DOI: 10.2489/jswc.69.6.564

results_short: They found rye cover crops increased soil water content early in the growoing season at two of the three sites studies.

introduction: 26 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2006-2008 in Columbus, OH investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Stefani Fae et al., 2009).
results_short: They found annual rye grass had no impact on corn silage yield.
Reviewers_results_long: Corn silage yields were statistically unimpacted by the cover crops (annual rye grass and oat/winter rye) included in this two year study. In the first year of the study, however, corn silage yields were lower when winter cover crops were grown. There was very little difference in yields between cover crop and no cover crop in the second year of the study.
methods: 26 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Aroostok + oat cv. Armor @ 90-95 and 50-84  kg/ha, annual ryegrass cv. Marshall @ 35-45 kg/ha, winter fallow (control).  26 Plots were an undescribed size.
citation: 26 Stefani Fa, G., Sulc, R.M., Barker, D.J., Dick, R.P., Eastridge, M.L., & Lorenz, N. (2009). Integrating winter annual forages into a no-till corn silage system. Agronomy Journal, 101: 1286-1296. DOI: 10.2134/agronj2009.0144

Reviewers_results_long: "In 2007, there were no significant differences in microbial biomass on a volumetric basis, whereas in 2008, oat + winter rye and annual ryegrass had greater microbial biomass than control."
methods: 26 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Aroostok + oat cv. Armor @ 90-95 and 50-84  kg/ha, annual ryegrass cv. Marshall @ 35-45 kg/ha, winter fallow (control).  26 Plots were an undescribed size.

introduction: 26 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2006-2008 in Columbus, OH investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Stefani Fae et al., 2009).
results_short: They found annual rye grass and oat/winter rye cover crops increased the amount of particulate organic matter in soils compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "Both cover crop treatments had greater particulate organic carbon than the no cover crop control. Th e 0-to 5-cm soil layer had more (P = 0.01) particulate organic carbon (3.64 kg m3) than the 5- to 15-cm layer (2.96 kg m3). There were no particulate organic carbon treatment interactions with depth or date."

introduction: 26 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2006-2008 in Columbus, OH investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Stefani Fae et al., 2009).
results_short: They found cover crops (annual rye grass or oat/winter rye mixtures) had no affect on soil penetration resistance (compaction) in the fall.
Reviewers_results_long: In the fall, cover crops had no effect on soil compaction. "This study showed that compaction was increased in the winter cover crop grazed treatments the first year [in the spring]. Nonetheless, 1 year later, soil compaction in both of the previously grazed cover crop treatments was reduced to levels that were similar to the control."

introduction: 27 A randomized complete block design study with 3 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2011-2014 in Jefferson City, MO investigating the effects of tillage, cover crops, and crop rotation in a maize/soybean system (Haruna & Nkongolo, 2015).
results_short: They found air filled pore space was unimpacted by rye cover crops.
Reviewers_results_long: There were no impacts of winter rye cover crops on air filled pore space compared to winter fallow in the second and third years of this study.
methods: 27 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye.  27 Plots were 148.84 sq m.
citation: 27 Haruna, S.I., & Nkongolo, N.V. (2015). Effects of tillage, rotation and cover crop on the physical properties of a silt-loam soil. International Agrophysics, 29: 137-145. DOI: 10.1515/intag-2015-0030

introduction: 27 A randomized complete block design study with 3 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2011-2014 in Jefferson City, MO investigating the effects of tillage, cover crops, and crop rotation in a maize/soybean system (Haruna & Nkongolo, 2015).
results_short: They found winter rye reduced soil bulk density in second year with no impact of cover crop in the third year.
Reviewers_results_long: Soil bulk density was lower in the second year of this study when winter rye cover crops were grown compared to winter fallow. In the third year, there were no differences in soil bulk density between winter rye and the control.

introduction: 28 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2009-2012 in Ames, IA, Crawfordsville, IA, Lewis, IA, Nashua, IA investigating the effects of cover crops and fertilization rate in a maize/soybean system (Pantoja et al., 2015).
results_short: They found moderate decrease in soil nitrate with winter rye immediately following termination of the cover crop and after maize harvest compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "Spring profile NO3N was measured only in corn plots with no nitrogen application. The NO3N was low at the time of rye cover crop control, and with 15 kg N ha-1 less with rye cover crop than no-rye cover crop. However, there was no difference from the rye cover crop in early June. Soil NO3N increased slightly with the rye cover crop from the preplant sampling to early June (8 kg N ha-1 increase), indicating some net nitrogen recycling to soil in the rye cover crop system; whereas with no-rye cover crop there was a slight decrease (4 kg N ha-1 less). In either case, change in soil NO3N was not large. "
methods: 28 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Wheeler @ 70 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 28 Cover crops were no-till drilled between September-October. 28 Plots were 20.7936 sq m.
citation: 28 Pantoja, J.L, Woli, K.P., Sawyer, J.E., & Barker, D.W. (2015). Corn nitrogen fertilization requirement and corn-soybean productivity with a rye cover crop. Soil Science Society of America Journal, 79: 1482-1495. DOI: 10.2136/sssaj2015.02.0084

In either case, change in soil NO3N was not large. "

introduction: 29 A randomized complete block design study with 4 or 3 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2006-2008 and 2006-2007 in Austin, MN, Felton, MN, Lamberton, MN, Rosemount, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a soybean system (Koch et al., 2015).
Response_var: abundance of aphids (Aphis glycines) over time
results_short: They found the abundance of soybean aphids reduced with winter rye cover crops compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long:
"In the present on-farm evaluation of this cover cropping system, A. glycines populations on soybean were suppressed in the system with the rye cover crop at five of six location-years."
crop remain to be determined.
methods: 29 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 67-157 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 29 Cover crops were no-till drilled between September-October. 29 Plots were 0.57 sq m or 0.51 sq m or 0.21 sq m or 0.500000000000001 sq m.
citation: 29 Koch, R.L., Sezen, Z., Porter, P.M., Ragsdale, D.W., Wyckhuys, K.A.G., & Heimpel, G.E. (2015). On-farm evaluation of a fall-seeded rye cover crop for suppression of soybean aphid (Hemiptera: Aphididae) on soybean. Agricultural and Forest Entomology, 17: 239-246. DOI: 10.1111/afe.12099

introduction: 29 A randomized complete block design study with 4 or 3 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2006-2008 and 2006-2007 in Austin, MN, Felton, MN, Lamberton, MN, Rosemount, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a soybean system (Koch et al., 2015).
Response_var: abundance of generalist foliage-foraging predators over times
results_short: They found higher number of cumulative predator-days in winter fallow compared to winter rye, but this could be due to the higher pest abundance in winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Significant differences in predator abundance were found between treatments at three of five location-years (predators were not recorded at one location-year). When these differences occurred, predators were more abundant on soybean without the cover crop, which is where aphid abundance was greatest. This suggests that predators were responding more to aphid density than to plant diversity or the rye cover crop per se.

introduction: 29 A randomized complete block design study with 4 or 3 replications was conducted at 4 sites from 2006-2008 and 2006-2007 in Austin, MN, Felton, MN, Lamberton, MN, Rosemount, MN investigating the effects of cover crops in a soybean system (Koch et al., 2015).
Response_var: exposure of aphid population to predators
results_short: They found exposure of aphid populations to predators similar among plots with winter rye and winter fallow except for marginal increases at one site in one year.
Reviewers_results_long: "The exposure analysis examining the biological control potential (i.e. cumulative predator-days per aphid) in the plots, revealed no significant differences between treatments at any location-year; however, at Lamberton in 2006, cumulative predator-days per aphid could be considered marginally higher in plots with rye compared with without rye (P=0.0586). Parasitoids were not included in analyses because only 16 parasitized aphids (i.e. mummies) were observed across all sample dates of all location-years (R. L. Koch, unpublished data)."

introduction: 30 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2010-2014 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cropping system in a maize system (Daigh et al., 2015).
Response_var: subsurface drainage annual flow weighted concentrations of nitrate (NO3-N)
results_short: They found winter rye cover crops reduced subsurface drainage concentrations and annual yields of nitrate.
Reviewers_results_long: Winter rye cover crop reduced subsurface nitrate yields and concentrations, but has no significant effect on phosphorous leachates.

introduction: 30 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2010-2014 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of cropping system in a maize system (Daigh et al., 2015).
Response_var: subsurface drainage total reactive phosphorous (TRP) annual concentrations
results_short: They found winter rye cover crops had no significant impact on subsurface drainage total reactive phosphorous annual conncentrations or yields
Reviewers_results_long: Flow-weighted total reactive phosphorous concentrations of subsurface drainage waters collected twice weekly were generally low when compared with other reports in the literature, ranging from <0.005 to 2.68 mg TRP L-1 with 0.04, 0.02, and 317 as the mean, median, and percent coefficient of variation, respectively. In contrast to the cumulative annual NO3N yields, cumulative annual total reactive phosphorous yields did not significantly differ among cropping systems.

introduction: 31 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2002-2004 in Urbana, IL investigating the effects of cover crops and fertilization rate in a maize system (Miguez & Bollero, 2006).
results_short: They found winter rye either reduced or had no affect on maize aboveground biomass compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Maize grown following hairy vetch cover crops consistently out performed maize grown after rye, rye/vetch mixture, and winter fallow even with fertilizers added (0, 90, 180, 270 kg N / ha). Maize productivity was stunted when grown after rye cover crops compared to all treatments examined including winter fallow.
methods: 31 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 90 kg/ha, hairy vetch @ 34 kg/ha, cereal rye + hairy vetch @ 68 and 28 kg/ha. 31 Cover crops were drilled between September-October. 31 Plots were 81 sq m.
citation: 31 Miguez, F.E., & Bollero, G.A. (2006). Winter cover crops in Illinois: Evaluation of ecophysiological characteristics of corn. Crop Science, 46(4): 1536-1545. DOI: 10.2135/cropsci2005.09.0306

introduction: 32 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2009-2010 in Urbana, IL investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Blesh & Drinkwater, 2014).

introduction: 33 A 6 x 3 factorial completely randomized design study with 2 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2010-2012 in Urbana, IL investigating the effects of compaction and cover crops in a soybean system (Acuna & Villamil, 2014).
results_short: They found soybean plants density decreased when a mixture of tillage radish and hairy vetch cover crops was grown  compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Soybean population was greatest when radish, radish/buckwheat, or no cover crop was grown. Soybean densities decreased when radish/hairy vetch, radish/triticale, or radish/rye preceeded soybean. Yields were most reduced with radish/rye cover crops.
methods: 33 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), radish @ 10 kg/ha, radish + buckwheat @ 5 and 45 kg/ha, radish + hairy vetch @ 5 and 30 kg/ha, radish + cereal rye @ 5 and 28 kg/ha, radish + winter triticale @ 5 and 38 kg/ha. 33Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 33 Plots were 37.0881 sq m.
citation: 33 Acuna, J.C., & Villamil, M.B. (2014). Short-term effects of cover crops and compaction on soil properties and soybean production in Illinois. Agronomy Journal, 106: 860-870. DOI: 10.2134/agronj13.0370

introduction: 33 A 6 x 3 factorial completely randomized design study with 2 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2010-2012 in Urbana, IL investigating the effects of compaction and cover crops in a soybean system (Acuna & Villamil, 2014).
results_short: They found soybean yields decreased when a mixture of tillage radish and winter rye cover crops  was grown compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Soybean yields were similar among radish, radish/buckwheat, radish/hairy vetch, radish/rye, and winter fallow treatments. Reduced yields were observed with radish/rye and radish triticale cover crops.

Reviewers_results_long: After one year of cover crops, there were no significant changes in the percent of water stable aggregates in the soil.
methods: 33 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), radish @ 10 kg/ha, radish + buckwheat @ 5 and 45 kg/ha, radish + hairy vetch @ 5 and 30 kg/ha, radish + cereal rye @ 5 and 28 kg/ha, radish + winter triticale @ 5 and 38 kg/ha. 33Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 33 Plots were 37.0881 sq m.
citation: 33 Acuna, J.C., & Villamil, M.B. (2014). Short-term effects of cover crops and compaction on soil properties and soybean production in Illinois. Agronomy Journal, 106: 860-870. DOI: 10.2134/agronj13.0370

introduction: 34 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2001-2003 in Brownstown, IL, Urbana, IL investigating the effects of crop rotation and fertilization rate in a maize/soybean system (Ruffo et al., 2004).
results_short: They found similar grain yields with winter rye compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Soybean grain yield was not affected by the treatments. Grand mean soybean grain yields was 2.8 Mg / ha. The variance component of the random effect of year (0.43 Mg2 / ha2) was 2.5 times larger than the residual (0.17 Mg2 / ha2). Thus, most of the variation in yields was due to the differences in environmental conditions experienced each year. The small contributions of the variance components of year x rotation (0 Mg2 / ha2) and year x N rate (0.01 Mg2 / ha2) interactions suggest that the weather conditions affected treatments equally and were the major determinant of grain yield.
methods: 34 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye (maize) / cereal rye (soybean) @ 90 kg/ha (rye), hairy vetch (maize) / cereal rye (soybean) @ 90 kg/ha (rye), hairy vetch + cereal rye (maize) / cereal rye (soybean) @ 90 kg/ha (rye).  34 Plots were 81 sq m.
citation: 34 Ruffo, M.L., Bullock, D.G., & Bollero, G.A (2004). Soybean yield as affected by biomass and nitrogen uptake of cereal rye in winter cover crop rotation. Agronomy Journal, 96(3): 800-805. DOI: 6abc

introduction: 35 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2001-2004 in Hancock, WI investigating the effects of cover crops and fertilization rate in a maize system (Andraski & Bundy, 2005).
results_short: They found maize grain yields were significantly higher when a winter cover crop was grown in the second and third year of the study compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "Subsequent corn grain yields were significantly higher in 2 of 3 years where cover crops were grown and were simliar following winter-filled oat, winter triticale, and winter rye with and without the top growth removed. The lack of significant grain yield differences between the rye cover crop with and without the top growth removed suggests that any benefical cover crop effect is mainly associated with the presence of a cover crop in the crop sequence rather than the top growth. In addition to the general benefit of providing wind erosion control on sandy soils, results from this study show that fall-planted cover crops such as oat, winter triticale, and winter rye can provide significant yield benefits to the subsequent corn crop at slightly lower nitrogen fertilizer rates (20 kg / ha) in some years."
methods: 35 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: oat cv. Gem @ 115 kg/ha, cereal rye cv. Spooner @ 145 kg/ha, cereal rye (top growth removed) cv. Spooner @ 145 kg/ha, winter triticale cv. Wolf River @ 145 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 35Cover crops were terminated with tillage. 35 Plots were an undescribed size.
citation: 35 Andraski, T.W., & Bundy, L.G. (2005). Cover crop effects on corn yield response to nitrogen on an irrigated sandy soil. Agronomy Journal, 97(4): 1239-1244. DOI: 10.2134/agronj2005.0052

introduction: 35 A split-plot randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2001-2004 in Hancock, WI investigating the effects of cover crops and fertilization rate in a maize system (Andraski & Bundy, 2005).
Response_var: soil nitrate (NO3-N) post winter cover crop, before planting cash crop
results_short: They found similar levels of soil nitrate with winter triticale compared to winter fallow two out of three years.
Reviewers_results_long: Compared to winter fallow, soil nitrate levels following cover crop termination were relatively unaffected by the winter cover crops used in this three year study (winter triticale, winter-filled oat, and winter rye). The only exception being winter triticale which had reduced soil nitrate levels in the second year of the study only.
methods: 35 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: oat cv. Gem @ 115 kg/ha, cereal rye cv. Spooner @ 145 kg/ha, cereal rye (top growth removed) cv. Spooner @ 145 kg/ha, winter triticale cv. Wolf River @ 145 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 35Cover crops were terminated with tillage. 35 Plots were an undescribed size.

introduction: 36 A randomized complete block design study with 10 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1996-2003 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of crop rotation and cover crops in a soybean/maize system (Kaspar et al., 2006).
results_short: They found similar bulk density values in plots with oat cover crops and winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "Bulk density corrected for landscape variation using terrain covariates was signficantly affected only by year and not by rotation phase, cover crop treatments, or interactions. Bulk density was significantly greater in 2001 than in 2000."
methods: 36 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: oat cv. Ogle, oat cv. Ogle + cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 3,800,000 rye seeds/ha, cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 3,800,000 rye seeds/ha, winter fallow (control). 36 Cover crops were overseeded into soybean in August. 36 Plots were 57.76 sq m.
citation: 36 Kaspar, T.C., Parkin, T.B., Jaynes, D.B., Cambardella, C.A., Meek, D.W., & Jung, Y.S. (2006). Examining changes in soil organic carbon with oat and rye cover crops using terrain covariates. Soil Science Society of Americal Journal, 70(4): 1168-1177. DOI: 10.2136/sssaj2005.0095

introduction: 36 A randomized complete block design study with 10 replications was conducted at 1 site from 1996-2003 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of crop rotation and cover crops in a soybean/maize system (Kaspar et al., 2006).

introduction: 37 A randomized complete block design study with 10 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2003-2005 in Ames, IA investigating the effects of crop rotation and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Parkin & Kaspar, 2006).
results_short: They found soil bulk density (0-30 cm depth) was similar with winter rye cover crops compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: In this no-tillage corn-soybean system, rye cover crops had no effect on soil properties, nitrous oxide fluxes, or crop yields.
methods: 37 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 3,800,000 seeds/ha. 37Cover crops were no-till drilled. 37 Plots were 14.44 sq m.

introduction: 38 A split-split-block latin square study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2014-2016 in Urbana, IL investigating the effects of crop rotation, tillage, and cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Dozier et al., 2017).

results_short: They found cover crops had no impact on soil ammonium concentrations compared to winter fallow.

introduction: 39 A spatially balanced complete block study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2009-2015 in Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Martinez-Feria et al., 2016).
results_short: They found rye winter cover crop led to reduced maize yields in two of the six years. Yields were similar in the other four years of the experiment.
Reviewers_results_long: "Statistically significant treatment effects (p < 0.05) were detected for grain yields and biomass in 2012 and 2013. The inclusion of a rye cover crop decreased maize yield by 34% (2.6 Mg / ha) and biomass by 22% (4.0 Mg / ha) when compared to continous corn in 2012. The cover crop yield penalty was less severe in 2013, with reductions of 22% (1.9 Mg / ha) in grain yield and 14% (2.6 Mg / ha) in biomass when compared to continuous corn. Both 2012 and 2013 were dry years. No significant treatment effects in maize biomass and grain yields were observed in 2009, 2010, 2011, and 2014. Across the six years, the average yield penalty in the continuous corn with rye cover crop was 6%."
methods: 39 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 300,000 seeds/ha, winter fallow (control). 39Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 39 Plots were 729 sq m.
citation: 39 Martinez-Feria, R.A., Dietzel, R., Liebman, M., Helmers, M.J., & Sotirios, V.A. (2016). Rye cover crop effects on maize: A system-level analysis. Field Crops Research, 196: 145-159. DOI: 10.1016/j.fcr.2016.06.016

introduction: 39 A spatially balanced complete block study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2009-2015 in Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Martinez-Feria et al., 2016).
results_short: They found nitrate loss through drainage water was reduced when rye was included as a cover crop in two of the six years of this experiment. Losses were similar in the other four years compared to no winter cover crop.
Reviewers_results_long: "Over the six-year period, inclusion of rye cover crop reduced measured cumulative drained water and nitrate losses in subsurface drainage by 12.1% and 20.4% respectively. However, statistically signficant treatment differences (p < 0.05) were not found in any of the studied years for annual water drainage, and only 2011 and 2012 for nitrate losses. When adjusted for nitrogen application rates nitrate losses were also only significantly reduced in 2011 and 2012, with 31% reduction in the amount of nitrate loss per kg of nitrogen applied. The highest nitrate loss values were recorded in the wet years for both treatments."
methods: 39 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 300,000 seeds/ha, winter fallow (control). 39Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 39 Plots were 729 sq m.
citation: 39 Martinez-Feria, R.A., Dietzel, R., Liebman, M., Helmers, M.J., & Sotirios, V.A. (2016). Rye cover crop effects on maize: A system-level analysis. Field Crops Research, 196: 145-159. DOI: 10.1016/j.fcr.2016.06.016

introduction: 39 A spatially balanced complete block study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2009-2015 in Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize system (Martinez-Feria et al., 2016).
results_short: They found nitrate loss through drainage water was reduced when rye was included as a cover crop in two of the six years of this experiment. Losses were similar in the other four years compared to no winter cover crop.
Reviewers_results_long: "Over the six-year period, inclusion of rye cover crop reduced measured cumulative drained water and nitrate losses in subsurface drainage by 12.1% and 20.4% respectively. However, statistically signficant treatment differences (p < 0.05) were not found in any of the studied years for annual water drainage, and only 2011 and 2012 for nitrate losses. When adjusted for nitrogen application rates nitrate losses were also only significantly reduced in 2011 and 2012, with 31% reduction in the amount of nitrate loss per kg of nitrogen applied. The highest nitrate loss values were recorded in the wet years for both treatments."
methods: 39 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Rymin @ 300,000 seeds/ha, winter fallow (control). 39Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 39 Plots were 729 sq m.

introduction: 40 A randomized complete block design study with 5 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2013-2015 at W.K. Kellogg Biological Station, MI, Arlington Agricultural Research Station, WI investigating the effects of cropping system in a maize system (Fox et al., 2016).
Response_var: mean percent sentinel egg removal per 48 hours (3 sampling events)
results_short: They found mixtures of winter rye and Austrian pea cover crops did not increase the invertebrate predation rates compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: "The inclusion of a winter annual cover crop did not increase the abundance or diversity of the invertebrate predator community or elevate predation rates. Although early in the growing season arthropod communities in cover crop systems differed from those occuring on bare soil in continuous maize, these differences did not continue after maize was planted. These results were consistent across both experimental years in both states. Instead, predator abundance, diversity and predation rates were similar in magnitude to annual maize without a cover crop"
methods: 40 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Cougar, Wheeler, Spooner + Austrian winter pea, winter fallow (control). 40Cover crops were terminated with herbicide and tillage. 40 Plots were 900 sq m.
citation: 40 Fox, A.F., Kim, T.N., Bahlai, C.A., Woltz, J.M., Gratton, C., & Landis, D.A. (2016). Cover crops have neutral effects on predator communities and biological control services in annual cellulosic bioenergy cropping systems. Agriculture, Ecosystems and Environment, 232: 101-109. DOI: 10.1016/j.agee.2016.07.003

introduction: 41 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2014-2017 in Lincoln, NE, Clay Center, NE investigating the effects of residue removal and cover crops in a maize system (Ruis et al., 2017).
Trt_id2description: rye winter cover crop, early termination
results_short: They found maize yields were similar when winter rye was grown as a cover crop compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Maize yields were among plots with winter rye cover crops and winter fallow in both irrigated and rainfed systems. There were also no differences in maize yields when winter rye was terminated during early spring or late (post seed head development).
methods: 41 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye @ 56-112 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 41Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 41 Plots were 104.04 sq m or 100 sq m.
citation: 41 Ruis, S.J., Blanco-Canqui, H., Jasa, P.J., Ferguson, R.B., & Slater, G. (2017). Can cover crop use allow increased levels of corn residue removal for biofuel in irrigated and rainfed systems?. Bioenergy Research, 10: 992-1004. DOI: 10.1007/s12155-017-9858-z

introduction: 41 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2014-2017 in Lincoln, NE, Clay Center, NE investigating the effects of residue removal and cover crops in a maize system (Ruis et al., 2017).
Response_var: mean weight diameter of water stable aggregates
Trt_id2description: rye winter cover crop, early termination
results_short: They found when winter rye was terminated late the mean weight of water stable aggregates increased compared to no cover crop and early termination.
Reviewers_results_long: "The results from this study show a decrease in the size of water-stable aggregates with complete residue removal at the rainfed site and general decrease in size of water-stable aggregates at the irrigated site after three years suggest that excessive residue removal could increase water erosion potential. The increase in wet aggregate stability with late-terminated cover crops and lack of change in wet aggegate stability between early-terminated cover crop and no cover crop at both sites strongly suggest that late-terminated cover crops can improve soil structural quality and reduce water erosion potential regardless of irrigation regime. The increased wet aggegate stability under late-terminated cover crop relative to early-terminated cover crop can be due to the greater biomass production under late-terminated cover crops."
methods: 41 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye @ 56-112 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 41Cover crops were terminated with herbicide. 41 Plots were 104.04 sq m or 100 sq m.
citation: 41 Ruis, S.J., Blanco-Canqui, H., Jasa, P.J., Ferguson, R.B., & Slater, G. (2017). Can cover crop use allow increased levels of corn residue removal for biofuel in irrigated and rainfed systems?. Bioenergy Research, 10: 992-1004. DOI: 10.1007/s12155-017-9858-z

results_short: They found winter rye did not affect total particulate organic matter (POM) in the soil during the three years of the study at the rainfed site. At the irrigated site, rye winter cover crops terminated late in the spring increased the quantity of POM.
Reviewers_results_long: In this three year study, winter rye had no effect on total particulate organic matter (POM) at the rainfed site. However, at the irrigated site, rye winter cover crops terminated late in the spring increased the quantity of POM in the soil.

introduction: 42 A randomized complete block design study with 4 or 5 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2013-2016 in Columbia, MO, Moberly, MO investigating the effects of cover crops or herbicide in a soybean system (Cornelius & Bradley, 2017).
results_short: They found of all the cover crops tested (cereal rye, winter wheat, annual ryegrass, Austrian winter peas, crimson clover, hairy vetch, oilseed radish, winter oats, and cereal rye mixed with hairy vetch) only cereal rye and cereal rye mixed with hairy vetch reduced early season waterhemp densities compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: These results indicated that cereal rye, Italian ryegrass, winter wheat, winter oat, crimson clover, Austrian winter pea, hairy vetch, oilseed radish, and cereal rye plus hairy vetch are each able to provide some degree of winter annual weed suppression, but that only certain cover crop species, such as cereal rye or cereal rye plus legume mixes, are able to provide reductions in early-season summer annual weed emergence similar to those seen with residual herbicide programs.
methods: 42 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: annual ryegrass cv. Marshall @ 28 kg/ha, winter wheat cv. Roane @ 135 kg/ha, oilseed radish cv. Tillage Radish @ 9 kg/ha, winter fallow (control), Austrian winter peas @ 56 kg/ha, hairy vetch @ 34 kg/ha, crimson clover @ 34 kg/ha, winter oats @ 78 kg/ha, cereal rye + hairy vetch @ 78 and 34 kg/ha, cereal rye @ 123 kg/ha.  42 Plots were 9 sq m.
citation: 42 Cornelius, C.D., & Bradley, K.W. (2017). Influence of various cover crop species on winter and summer annual weed emergence in soybean. Weed Technology, 31: 503-513. DOI: 10.1017/wet.2017.23

introduction: 42 A randomized complete block design study with 4 or 5 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2013-2016 in Columbia, MO, Moberly, MO investigating the effects of cover crops or herbicide in a soybean system (Cornelius & Bradley, 2017).

results_short: They found all the cover crop studied decreased the density of winter weeds.

introduction: 43 A randomized complete block design study with 2 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2011-2014 in Gilmore City, IA, Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cover crops in a maize/soybean system (Dunbar et al., 2017).
Response_var: total abundance of ants (Formicidae) on soil surface (pitfall traps in maize)
results_short: They found the abundance of ants (Formicidae) collected from the soil surface in maize and soybean were unaffected by the inclusion of a rye winter cover crop compared to winter fallow.
Reviewers_results_long: Most invertebrate taxa collected from both the soil surface and on aboveground crop tissue were unaffected by the inclusion of a rye winter cover crop compared to winter fallow in this three year study. The exceptions were crickets (decreased abundance with cover crops) and beetles (increased abundance with cover crops).
methods: 43 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye @ 63-100 kg/ha. 43Cover crops were no-till drilled. 43 Plots were 225 sq m.
citation: 43 Dunbar, M.W., Gassmann, A.J., & O'Neal, M.E. (2017). Limited impact of a fall-seeded, spring-terminated rye cover crop on beneficial arthropods. Environmental Entomology, 46(2): 284-290. DOI: 10.1093/ee/nvw177

introduction: 44 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2013-2014 in Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cropping system in a maize system (Meng et al., 2016).
Response_var: fraction of soil organic nitrogen mineralized in 30 days (frozen before incubation)
results_short: They found soil organic nitrogen mineralization increased with cover crops compared to no cover crops when soils were frozen. Mineralization rates were similar when soils were not frozen.
Reviewers_results_long: Nitrogen mineralization rates increased with cereal rye cover crops compared to winter fallow when soils experience a freeze-thaw cycle. Cereal rye cover crops had no effects on nitrogen mineralization when the soils remained unfrozen.
methods: 44 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: winter fallow (control), cereal rye.  44 Plots were 729 sq m.
citation: 44 Meng, Y., Chua-Ona, T., & Thompson, M.L. (2016). Short-term nitrogen mineralization potential in soils of biofuel cropping systems. Soil Science, 181(11/12): 503-512. DOI: 10.1097/SS.0000000000000187

introduction: 44 A randomized complete block design study with 4 replications was conducted at 1 site from 2013-2014 in Boone County, IA investigating the effects of cropping system in a maize system (Meng et al., 2016).
results_short: They found cereal rye winter cover crops had no affect on soil organic carbon content (0-15 cm depth).
Reviewers_results_long: Rye winter cover crops had no effects on the soil parameters measured in this experiment which included organic carbon, total nitrogen, inorganic nitrogen (i.e. ammonium and nitrate), and pH.

introduction: 45 A split-strip-plot randomized complete block design study with 2 replications was conducted at 2 sites from 2012-2014 at Kellogg Biological Station, MI, Mason Research Farm, MI investigating the effects of topographical position, crop phase, tillage, and cover crop in a maize/soybean system (Negassa et al., 2015).
Trt_id1description: no winter cover crop, summit location
Trt_id2description: rye winter cover crop, summit location
results_short: They found carbon dioxide emissions increased with winter rye cover crops compared to no cover crop in the depression and slope locations within a field.
Reviewers_results_long: "Presence of rye cover crop increased carbon dioxide emissions across all topographical positions; however, counterintuitively, the largest increases in carbon dioxide emissions due to cover crop presence were observed in the depression areas where amounts of rye biomass inputs were the lowest. Across both years and both study sites, the regression slopes between carbon dioxide emissions and temperatures were significantly higher in the cover crop than in the no cover plots."
methods: 45 Plots received one of the following cover crop treatments: cereal rye cv. Aroostok @ 112 kg/ha, winter fallow (control). 45 Cover crops were drilled between October-November. 45 Plots were an undescribed size.
citation: 45 Negassa, W., Price, R.F., Basir, A., Snapp, S.S., & Kravchenko, A. (2015). Cover crop and tillage systems effect on soil CO2 and N2O fluxes in contrasting topographic positions. Soil & Tillage Research, 154: 64-74. DOI: 10.1016/j.still.2015.06.015
